# YesStore — Product Specification for Integration

**Document purpose:** Describe what YesStore does so it can be incorporated into the master project.  
**Audience:** Product, design, and frontend/backend teams planning integration.  
**Scope:** Application behaviour, data model, screens, and user flows only — no hosting, deployment, or infrastructure detail.

---

## 1. Overview

YesStore is a **warehouse location photo manager**. It lets authorised staff browse a fixed physical layout (racks → rows → bins → items), attach **one or more photos** at every level, and record **multiple stock items per bin**.

Primary use case: walk the warehouse with a phone, open a bin, photograph the bin and each item inside, and later look up any location visually.

The app is designed for **mobile use** and can be **installed on the home screen** (PWA) for a full-screen, app-like experience with direct camera access.

---

## 2. Users & Access

| Aspect | Behaviour |
|--------|-----------|
| **Who can use it** | Registered users only; unauthenticated visitors see a login screen |
| **Login field** | User enters a **User ID** (e.g. `admin`, `warehouse1`) — not a full email address |
| **Password** | Standard password (minimum 6 characters) |
| **Registration** | New users can self-register with User ID + password |
| **Session** | Stays signed in until explicit sign-out |
| **Display** | Signed-in User ID shown in the header |

**Integration note:** The master project may map User ID to its own identity system; the UX expectation is a short, memorable login name rather than an email field.

